english:
  title: Postscript on Reading the Poems of Tao Yuanming by Master Dongting
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: "From the Jin Dynasty to the present day, more than a thousand years have passed, yet the world continues to praise the character of Tao Yuanming. I have long believed that by examining his age and reciting his poems, one may come to know the man himself. During that time of division between north and south, when warfare followed upon warfare and the people knew no peace—when internal strife was imminent and the royal house crumbling—surely this was the moment for righteous men of noble spirit to stand forth. Yet Tao Yuanming merely withdrew to the countryside. When I examine his poems—those on begging for food, on the hardship of poverty, on grievance, on wine-drinking—they seem but expressions of a man overwhelmed by desolation, who sought solace in wine to pass the days. How then has he come to be celebrated through the ages?\n\nDu Fu once wrote:\n\"Tao Qian, that old man fleeing the world—\nHe may not have truly grasped the Way.\nHis collected poems, I confess,\nStrike me as withered and dry.\"\n\nHan Yu, upon reading the \"Record of the Land of Wine,\" observed: \"Even Ruan Ji and Tao Qian could not find peace of mind, but rather were moved by the circumstances and judgments of things, and so took refuge in escape.\" These two are esteemed scholars of their time, versed in discerning character, yet their words left me all the more perplexed.\n\nBut recently, when I obtained Master Dongting's postscript to the poems of Tao Yuanming, which states: \"Though worn down by the hardships of hunger and cold, there dwells within a serene joy. Though submerged in the fog of fermented grain, there shines forth a transcendent integrity\"—upon reading these words, I found myself sighing without knowing why: \"Ah! This is why he was Tao Yuanming! Though a thousand years divide us, it is as if I hear his voice and see his countenance.\"\n\n\"Moreover, his wearing down by hunger and cold, his immersion in the haze of wine—these are traces, external things. His serene joy and transcendent integrity—these are of the heart, internal things. The external is easy to perceive; the internal is difficult to know. It is fitting that later scholars have not penetrated his inner sanctuary. The words of Du Fu and Han Yu were perhaps spoken with a certain ulterance.\"\n\nWhen I voiced this thought, Master Dongting replied: \"It is not so. Tao Yuanming was born in a degenerate age and perceived that his time could not be redeemed. He walked a lofty path and withdrew far, nourishing his true nature beneath humble gates and thatch. He regarded official rank as dust and considered ten thousand measures of salary worthless. Though his sustenance was meager, he found joy in this simplicity and forgot his sorrows. When his nation fell and ages turned, while his contemporaries sought each other out to take office, Tao Yuanming stood apart. His loyalty to the former court remained clear as the blue sky and white sun. He would not serve two rulers, but hid himself in poetry and wine. His lofty character and resolute integrity—not even the piercing chill of autumn frost can compare!\n\n\"In his poems, when sorrow comes, he writes of sorrow; when joy comes, he writes of joy; when he drinks wine, he writes of drinking wine. When he writes:\n'In summer I endure constant hunger,\nIn cold nights I sleep without a quilt,'\nCan we not perceive the depth of his hardship? Yet when he writes:\n'Laughing beneath the eastern window,\nAgain I know the joy of this simple life,'—\nIs this not the serenity he discovered? When he writes:\n'I pound the grain and brew fine wine,\nWhen it is ready, I pour and drink alone,'\nAnd again:\n'If in the morning I live with righteousness,\nWhat more need I ask, though I die at evening?'—\nIs there not within his immersion a transcendent integrity? \n\n\"The joy of Tao Yuanming never departs from hunger and cold, nor his integrity from the depths of wine. Why? Because he saw the salary of ten thousand measures as unjust and chose willingly the life of the fields, thus hunger and cold became his joy. Because he took refuge in wine yet never abandoned his purpose, thus his apparent haze became his integrity. How can we separate the inner from the outer?\"\n\nI bowed and said, \"I understand,\" and withdrew to record these words."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Master Dongting (東亭先生): Refers to a contemporary scholar whose insights into Tao Yuanming''s character deeply impressed the author.'
  - key: ''
    value: The four poems referenced here are famous works by Tao Yuanming that illustrate the tension between external hardship and internal spiritual freedom.
  - key: ''
    value: Du Fu (杜子美, 712-770) and Han Yu (韓退之, 768-824) were celebrated Tang Dynasty poets and scholars whose earlier criticism of Tao Yuanming prompted this reconsideration.
